===Noun===
{{en-noun}}
{{wikipedia}}

# {{lb|en|colloquial}} A person with a special interest in or knowledge of [[food]], a [[gourmet]].
#: {{ux|en|We self-professed '''foodies''' liked to meet in restaurants and talk like experts about what we were eating.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Ann Barr|authorlink=Ann Barr|author2=Paul Levy|authorlink2=Paul Levy (journalist)|title=The Official Foodie Handbook: Be Modern–Worship Food|year=1984|publisher=Ebury Press|location=London|page=6|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/officialfoodieha0000barr/page/n7/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-85223-343-6|passage='''Foodies''' are the ones talking about food in any gathering—salivating over restaurants, recipes, radicchio. They don't think they are being trivial–'''Foodies''' consider food to be an art, on a level with painting or drama.}}
#* {{quote-web|en|author=Steven Poole|url=http://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/sep/28/lets-start-foodie-backlash|title=Let's start the foodie backlash|date=2012-09-28|work=The Guardian|passage=“Foodie” has now pretty much everywhere replaced “gourmet”, perhaps because the latter more strongly evokes privilege and a snobbish claim to uncommon sensory discrimination—even though those qualities are rampant among the “'''foodies'''” themselves.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2014|author=Josee Johnston|author2=Shyon Baumann|title=Foodies: Democracy and Distinction in the Gourmet Foodscape|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317745006||url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FmW2BQAAQBAJ&lpg=PT65&dq=%22foodies%22&hl=es&pg=PT60#v=onepage&q&f=false|text=While the ''Foodie Handbook'' is now decades old, its message strikes a chord with contemporary '''foodie''' discourse, touching on themes like the abysmal quality of mainstream food (e.g., “cheese in plastic-wrapped portions”), the appeal of '''foodie''' accoutrement like chefs' knives and gas stoves, as well as the importance of thinking and talking about food (as opposed to just eating well—“pigs can eat well”) (1984: 6–7).}}

